04633nam a22006375i 9780228012177DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a2022361764  a97802280121777 a10.1515/97802280121772doi  a(DE-B1597)657018  a(OCoLC)1283496937  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA00aBP67.C2bZ56 2022 7aSOC0480002bisacsh04a305.235088297223  aMG 729682rvk0(DE-625)rvk/122861:122321 aZine, Jasmin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnder Siege :bIslamophobia and the 9/11 Generation /cJasmin Zine. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAdvancing Studies in Religion00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tIdentity, Citizenship, and Belonging in an Age of Islamophobia -- tThe 9/11 Generation and the Dynamics of Islamophobia -- tCampus Culture in an Age of Islamophobia and Empire -- tIslamophobia and the Security Industrial Complex -- tBeing Cast as the Bogeyman -- tMuslim Counterpublics -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe 9/11 attacks in the United States, the subsequent global “war on terror,” and the proliferation of domestic security policies in Western nations have had a profound impact on the lives of young Muslims, whose identities and experiences have been shaped within and against these conditions. The millennial generation of Muslim youth has come of age in these turbulent times, dealing with the aftermath and backlash associated with these events.Under Siege explores the lives of Canadian Muslim youth belonging to the 9/11 generation as they navigate these fraught times of global war and terror. While many studies address contemporary manifestations of Islamophobia and anti-Muslim racism, few have focused on the toll this takes on Muslim communities, especially among younger generations. Based on in-depth interviews with more than 130 young people, youth workers, and community leaders, Jasmin Zine’s ethnographic study unpacks the dynamics of Islamophobia as a system of oppression and examines its impact on Canadian Muslim youth. Covering topics such as citizenship, identity and belonging, securitization, radicalization, campus culture in an age of empire, and subaltern Muslim counterpublics and resistance, Under Siege provides a unique and comprehensive examination of the complex realities of Muslim youth in a post-9/11 world.Twenty years after the 9/11 attacks, Zine reveals how the global war on terror and heightened anti-Muslim racism have affected a generation of Canadians who were socialized into a world where their faith and identity are under siege.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIslamophobiazCanada. 0aMuslim youthzCanadavInterviews. 0aMuslim youthzCanadaxEthnic identity. 0aMuslim youthzCanadaxSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aMuslim youthzCanadaxSocial conditions. 0aMuslim youthzCanada. 0aMuslimsxCrimes againstzCanada. 0aWar on Terrorism, 2001-2009xPsychological aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Islamic Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311127214608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022z978311127419540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022801217740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228012177423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228012177/original  a978-3-11-127214-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-127419-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyt